NLP-BASED COST SYNERGY ANALYSIS¶

The project is the result of numerous post-merger integration failures resulting from long lead times to synergy realisation. It is imperative for entities involved in an M&A transaction to quickly identify overlapping costs and take rapid action in eliminating those costs. Here, I aim at building a model that can predict the spend category a general cost item belongs to based on the text description of the item itself. Hence, the goal is to predict common spend categories, for the items of both the target and the acquirer, in order to gauge the cost overlaps for each cost category and act upon the most "synergy-promising".

This will be done by tuning an NLP algorithm that uses an expense's most granular label (Commodity Name) to predict the three least granular (most general) labels of the same expense (Category Name, Subcategory Name, Segment Name). The model was trained on the UNSPC dataset, a dataset that classifies products & items in a standardised way for industrial purposes. After appropriate training, the model will be used on testing data to predict the common cost category for each item in each entity and analyse and prioritise the most significant synergy opportunities.

Before going through the EDA, the Data Preprocessing and the Model Fit, we load all the functions and packages we need to perform the first steps. These include numpy, pandas, nltk, sklearn, re and matplotlib.

As shown for all the three labels, the distribution of the classes is heavily unbalanced. Hence, we understand it is crucial to tune the hyperparameters of the model picked by trying to maximise the F1-score rather than accuracy. In fact, F1-score, unlike accuracy, accounts for unbalanced classes when measuring performance.

Data Preprocessing¶

In order to predict the three highest levels in the spending heirarchy (Category, Subcategory, and Segment) using the lowest level (Commodity), we will need to transform the commodity names into a format that is suitable for machine learning. Thus, we will use a TF-IDF vectorizer to transpose these character strings into a matrix of 0s and 1s. In this matrix, each row will be represented by a commodity name (document), and each column by a word that appears in some (the exact number is to be tuned) of the commodity names present in the dataset.

Before passing the input data (the commodity names) through the vectorizer to get it in a format that can be used for prediction, we believed it would be useful to first lemmatize the words that appear in the list of commodity names. Lemmatization is the process of grouping together the different inflected forms of a word so they can be analyzed as a single item. Lemmatization is similar to stemming but it doesn't reduce some words to the point that they are no longer in the dictionary (which happens in many cases with stemming). Thus, lemmatization links words with similar meanings to one word. Lemmatization is useful for our task because, without it, some words ("egg") and their plural form ("eggs") or other inflected forms of it would be considered as entirely different objects, when in reality they refer to the same thing. Grouping these different forms together should increase the performance of our model.

In [8]:
# Find lexical category of a word to understand its context
def getWordNetPOS(word):
    tag = nltk.pos_tag([word])[0][1][0].upper()
    tagDict = {"J": wordnet.ADJ,
               "N": wordnet.NOUN,
               "V": wordnet.VERB,
               "R": wordnet.ADV}
    return tagDict.get(tag, wordnet.NOUN)

# Lemmatize the word. If string isn't a word in the english dictionary then it's not changed
def lemmatize_word(word):
    return WordNetLemmatizer().lemmatize(word, getWordNetPOS(word))

Next, we need to define a customer transformer that can be included as the first step in the pipeline we will build, so that all the words in the list of commodity names are lemmatized before being passed through the TF-IDF vectorizer.

In [11]:
# Defining custom transformer
class CustomTransformer(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self, your_function):
        self.your_function = your_function

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self

    def transform(self, X):
        return self.your_function(X)
    
    
# Defining a function that applies the lemmatization transformation to all input data
def lemmatize_input_strings(word_list):
    word_list = word_list.str.lower().apply(lambda x: re.sub("[^A-Za-z0-9]+", ' ', x)) # Lower-case & drop special-characters apart from hyphen and apostrophe
    word_list = word_list.apply(lambda x: " ".join(list(map(lemmatize_word, x.split(" "))))) # Lemmatize
    return word_list

Tuning the model to maximize F1-score through 5-fold cross validation¶

NOTE: the function tune_random_forest deploys a manual hyperparameters tuning. We needed to tune the hyperparameters in order to get the highest F1-score on the lowest (most granular) predicted level of hierarchy (Segment Name). Since the GridSearchCV function does not allow to specify the F1-score of a specific variable as a scoring parameter, we had to define a kind of custom logic to extract that result and choose the combination of hyperparameters according to that result.

In [12]:
# Assign the input data to X and the output data to y 
X = df['Commodity Name']
y = df[['Category Name', 'Subcategory Name', 'Segment Name']]
In [1]:
# Define a function that will tune random forest over the specified lists of parameters and store the
# results in a dataframe
def tune_random_forest(X, y, tfidf_min_df, tfidf_sublinear_tf, rf_n_estimators, rf_criterion, 
                        rf_min_samples_leaf, rf_max_features):
    
    X_lem=lemmatize_input_strings(X)
    # Generate random indexes that will define the 5 folds used for cross validation
    kf = KFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=1)
    # Create empty lists for f1 scores
    f1_fold_scores_1 = []
    f1_fold_scores_2 = []
    f1_fold_scores_3 = []
    f1_scores_1 = []
    f1_scores_2 = []
    f1_scores_3 = []

    # Create empty lists to store the parameter sets
    a_s = []
    b_s = []
    c_s = []
    d_s = []
    e_s = []
    f_s = []
   
    i=0
    
    for a in tfidf_min_df:
        for b in tfidf_sublinear_tf:
            for c in rf_n_estimators:
                for d in rf_criterion:
                    for e in rf_min_samples_leaf:
                        for f in rf_max_features:
                                        # Create the pipeline
                                        pipe_rf = Pipeline([
                                            ('tfidf', TfidfVectorizer(
                                                stop_words="english",
                                                dtype=np.float32,
                                                min_df=a,
                                                sublinear_tf=b)),
                                            ('clf', MultiOutputClassifier(estimator=RandomForestClassifier(
                                                n_estimators=c,
                                                criterion=d,
                                                min_samples_leaf=e,
                                                max_features=f,
                                                random_state=10)))
                                        ])
                                        for j, (train_index, test_index) in enumerate(kf.split(X_lem, y)):
                                            # Fit the pipeline on the training data
                                            pipe_rf.fit(X_lem[train_index], y.loc[train_index, :])
                                            print(i)
                                            i += 1
                                            # Make predictions on the test set
                                            y_pred = pipe_rf.predict(X_lem[test_index])
                                            y_test_vals = y.loc[test_index,:].values
                                            
                                            # Calculate and store F1-scores for each fold
                                            f1_1 = f1_score(y_test_vals[:, 0], y_pred[:, 0], average='weighted')
                                            f1_2 = f1_score(y_test_vals[:, 1], y_pred[:, 1], average='weighted')
                                            f1_3 = f1_score(y_test_vals[:, 2], y_pred[:, 2], average='weighted')
                                            
                                            f1_fold_scores_1.append(f1_1)
                                            f1_fold_scores_2.append(f1_2)
                                            f1_fold_scores_3.append(f1_3)
                                        
                                        # Store mean F1-scores for each set of parameters
                                        f1_scores_1.append(sum(f1_fold_scores_1)/5)
                                        f1_scores_2.append(sum(f1_fold_scores_2)/5)
                                        f1_scores_3.append(sum(f1_fold_scores_3)/5)
                                
                                        f1_fold_scores_1=[]
                                        f1_fold_scores_2=[]
                                        f1_fold_scores_3=[]
                                        a_s.append(a)
                                        b_s.append(b)
                                        c_s.append(c)
                                        d_s.append(d)
                                        e_s.append(e)
                                        f_s.append(f)


    # Create a dictionary for the results
    results_dict = {
        'tfidf_min_dfs': a_s,
        'tfidf_sublinear_tfs': b_s,
        'rf_n_estimators': c_s,
        'rf_criterions': d_s,
        'rf_min_samples_leaf': e_s,
        'rf_max_features': f_s,
        'rf_f1_scores_1': f1_scores_1,
        'rf_f1_scores_2': f1_scores_2,
        'rf_f1_scores_3': f1_scores_3
    }

    # Create a DataFrame from the results dictionary
    results_df = pd.DataFrame(results_dict).sort_values(by=['rf_f1_scores_3'], ascending=False)
    return results_df

We will now tune the random forest over the following parameters: tfidf_min_df, tfidf_sublinear_tf, rf_criterion, rf_min_samples_leaf, and rf_max_features. We will keep rf_n_estimators constant at the default value of 100 so that the tuning process doesn't take too long. Moreover, rf_n_estimators cannot be tuned as a higher number of tree estimators will always increase the performance of a random forest ensamble. However, for the final model, which will be trained over the whole dataset, we will use a larger value for the n_estimators parameter (250), and keep the other parameters as the ones that delivered the highest f1-score for the segment category in the tuning process below.

Relabelling observations without words in the vectorizer as unclassified¶

Even though the our random forest model will make predictions for obvservations whose item descriptions have no words appearing in the vectorizer matrix, we believe that it is best to label these observations as unclassified rather than relying on the predictions of the model. Therefore, we will attempt to isolate the observations from the client spend data whose descriptions have no words appearing in the pipeline vectorizer and manually label them as unclassifed. We will then analyze the nature of these items and their relative importance within the client's total spend. We'll then proceed to look for any meaningful words within the descriptions of these observations that we might use to manually label these observations and update the training dataset.

Extracting possibly classifiable items from the unclassified items with the highest spend¶

In [26]:
# Define a function which keeps a word if it's in the English dictionary
def is_in_dictionary(x):
    # Load the English dictionary
    with open('english2.txt', 'r') as dictionary_file:
        dictionary = set(word.strip().lower() for word in dictionary_file)
    if x in dictionary and len(x)>3:
        return x
    else:
        return ""

def extract_classifiable_observations(unclassified_obs):
    # Identify words in the English dictionary within the item descriptions of the unclassified observations
    # and join these words together in a new series
    dictionary_words_in_obs = unclassified_obs.str.lower().apply(lambda x: (" ".join(list(map(is_in_dictionary, 
                            re.sub("[^A-Za-z0-9]+", ' ', x).split())))).strip()).to_frame(name="Dictionary words")
    # Merge the raw item descriptions and their associated extracted words
    unclassified_obs=unclassified_obs.to_frame().merge(dictionary_words_in_obs, left_index=True, right_index=True)
    # Return only the observations with item descriptions that contained words in the English dictionary and were extracted
    return unclassified_obs[unclassified_obs["Dictionary words"]!=""]

# Take the first 100 unclassified spends from the client data by net value and return only the items with words
# in the english dictionary.
classifiable_observations=extract_classifiable_observations(spending_unclassified.loc[0:99, "Short Text"])

Final Comments¶

Now we can safely conclude we obtained an extremely accurate model, with an F1-score on the testing set of approximately 90%. Moreover, it is crucial to highlight that the model has been trained to maximise robustness besides accuracy. In fact, the decision to Lemmatize words and exclude the lemmas that were not in the dictionary aims at preventing the model's overfitting. In fact, the training set only includes words that potentially have a substantial meaning in any context.

The model is now ready to be applied to M&A transactions involving entities in any industry.
